The learning2014 data set describes students in the Introduction to Social Statistics course in 2014. The number of students is 166, and all of them participated in the course exam.

The learning2014 data set consists of seven variables:

  1. Gender.
  2. Age in years.
  3. Global attitude toward statistics.
  4. Mean answer to questions reflecting deep learning.
  5. Mean answer to questions reflecting strategic learning.
  6. Mean answer to questions reflecting surface learning.
  7. Points achieved in the exam.

THIRD, I explored the variables of the learning2014 data in more detail.

This corresponds to the data analysis part of Exercise 2, its 2. task.

Of the 166 students, 110 were female. The mean (range) age of students was 25.5 (17-55) years. Their global attitude toward statistics ranged from 1.4 to 5.0 with a mean value of 3.1. Variables describing deep, strategic, and surface learning resulted in the following mean (range) values, respectively: 3.7 (1.6-4.9), 3.1 (1.3-5.0), and 2.8 (1.6-4.3). FOURTH, I fitted a linear regression model with exam points as a target variable.

This corresponds to the data analysis part of Exercise 2, its 3. and 4. tasks.

To select explanatory variables to the model I created a plot matrix.

library(GGally)

Based on correlations of potential explanatory variables with the target variable together with a visual inspection of the plot matrix I selected attitude, strategic learning, and surface learning as explanatory variables.

my_model1 <- lm(Points ~ atti + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
summary(my_model1)

As attitude was the only explanatory variable with p-value <0.05, I excluded strategic and surface learning from the model and fitted a new model with attitude as an explanatory variable.

my_model2 <- lm(Points ~ atti, data = learning2014)
summary(my_model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ atti, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## atti          3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

The equation of the model is: y = 11.6 + 3.5 * attitude. The equation indicates that when a students attitude increases with 1 in a scale from 1 to 5, his/her exam points increases with 3.5 points. For example, if the attitude is 1, the expected exam points are 15 and, correspondingly, when the attitude is 5, the expected exam points are 29. Based on the model, attitude explains 19% of the variation in exam points (R2 = 0.19).

FIFTH, I produced diagnostic plots for the model.

This corresponds to the data analysis part of Exercise 2, its 5. task.

?plot.lm
## starting httpd help server ... done
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model2, which = c(1,2,5))

Based on the scatter plot of model residuals versus model predictions, model errors had constant variance. The size of the error did not depend on the explanatory variable. The plot showed no patterns but a random spread of errors.

Based on the Q-Q-plot, model errors were normally distributed with a mean value of 0. The plot showed a reasonable fit of errors with the straight line.

Based on the plot of residuals versus leverage, there were no single observations with exceptionally high impact on the model results.

The alc data set describes students of two Portuguese schools, their age, gender, socio-demographics, free-time including alcohol use, health status, etc. The data set consists of 370 students and 35 variables. Prof.Paulo Cortez (http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/Home.html) is the provider of the original data set (Student Performance Data Set, https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance).

THIRD, I selected four potential explanatory variables for alcohol consumption from the alc data set, explored them, and hypothesized their relationships with alcohol consumption.

This corresponds to the data analysis part of Exercise 3, its 3. and 4. tasks.

The first potential explanatory variable for alcohol consumption was sex, as, in general, there are gender differences in alcohol consumption (Wilsnack et al.2000 https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1046/j.1360-0443.2000.95225112.x). I hypothesized that males consume more alcohol and are more often heavy drinkers than females.

The number of males in the alc data is 175, and that of females is 195. Of the 175 males, 70 i.e.41% are heavy drinkers, whereas of the 195 females only 41 i.e.21% are heavy drinkers, which appears to support the hypothesis.

The second potential explanatory variable for alcohol consumption was age. I expected that the proportion of heavy drinkers increases together with age.

alc %>% group_by(high_use) %>% summarise(count = n(), mean_age = mean(age))

The mean age of heavy drinking students was 16.8 years and that of non-heavy drinking students was 16.5 years. Based on the box plot the median age of heavy-drinking students was 17 years and that of non-heavy drinking students was 16 years. Thus, the age distribution slightly suggested that heavy-drinking students are older.

The third potential explanatory variable for alcohol consumption was goout that indicates going out with friends as a numeric values from 1 (very low frequency) to 5 (very high frequency). By and large, friends drinking behavior is related to adolescents drinking (Bot et al.2005 https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0306460304003314) and, consequently, I expected going out with friends associates with heavy-drinking also in the alc data.

g2 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = high_use, y = goout))
g2 + geom_boxplot() + xlab("Heavy drinking") + ylab("Going out intensity") + ggtitle("Heavy and non-heavy drinking students by going out with friends")

The distribution of the goout variable suggested that heavy drinking students go out with friends more frequently and/or with higher intensity than non-heavy drinking students. This supports my hypothesis.

The fourth potential explanatory variable for alcohol consumption was address that indicates living in an urban (U) or rural area (R). I chose this variable because in some European countries, such as Germany, adolescents living in rural areas appear to be more susceptible to drinking problems (Donath et al.2011 https://bmcpublichealth.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1471-2458-11-84).

alc %>% group_by(address, high_use) %>% count

In the alc data, the number of students living in rural areas was 81 and that of students living in urban areas was 289. Of the 81 rural students, 31 i.e.38% was heavy drinkers, whereas of the 289 urban students only 28% were heavy drinkers. This supports my hypothesis that living in a rural area predispose students to drinking problems.

FOURTH, I performed logistic regression to explore the relationship between the four selected explanatory variables (sex, age, goout, address) and alcohol consumption. As a target variables, I used the binary high_use variable.

m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + age + goout + address, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Based on the logistic regression model with sex, age, goout, and address as explanatory variables, male gender, going out with friends, and living in a rural area increased the odds of being a heavy drinker. The odds of men was 2.5-times the odds of women (OR, 95% CI: 2.51, 1.54-4.15). One point increase in the going out scale increased the odds by 2.2 (OR, 95% CI: 2.16, 1.71-2.77). The odds of students living in an urban area was 0.5-times the odds of students living in a rural area (OR, 95% CI: 0.52, 0.29-0.94). With respect to age, the 95% CI for the OR contained 1, which denotes that age had no statistically significant effect on the OR. The result supported my hypotheses except for age.

FIFTH, I explored the predictive power of the model.

m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + age + goout + address, data = alc, family = "binomial")
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability >0.5)
select(alc, sex, age, goout, address, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

The training error of the model i.e.the total proportion on inaccurately classified individuals was (16+65)/(243+16+65+46)*100 = 21.9%. The model was better in predicting non-heavy drinking students. Of the 111 heavy-drinkers the model correctly recognized only 46 (41%), whereas of the 259 non-heavy drinkers the model correctly recognized 243 (94%).

SIXTH, I carried out the BONUS task and performed 10-fold cross-validation on my model.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2189189
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2405405

In my model, the original prediction error was 21.9%. In the 10-fold cross-validation, the mean prediction error increased to 25.1% still being a slightly lower than that of the DataCamp model (25.9%). Consequently, sex, age, goout, and address appear to form a bit better combination of explanatory variables than those used in the DataCamp model.

There are some strong correlations (r >0.70) across the Boston data variables. The strong positive correlations are tax x rad (r = 0.91), nox x indus (r = 0.76), nox x age (r = 0.73), and tax x indus (r = 0.72). Correspondingly, the strong negative correlations are nox x dis (r = -0.77), age x dis (r = -0.75), medv x lstat (r = -0.74), and dis x indus (r = -0.71).

Based on the total of within cluster sum of squares (WCSS), I chose 2 as the optimal number of clusters. Actually, the two clusters solution did not much differ from the four clusters solution, but they both highlighted the same variables, such as crim and zn, as the most representative factors.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(km$cluster)
plot(lda.fit2, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit2, myscale = 2)

In this four clusters solution, the Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise) was the main driver of clustering. It separated Cluster 1 from other clusters.

biplot(pca_human2, cex = c(0.5, 0.5), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = "PC1 (54%) Education, life-expectancy, and maternal weel-being", ylab = "PC2 (16%) Female participation in the society")

The results of the first PCA based on non-standardized variables differed from those of the second PCA based on standardized variables. In the first, the components represent mainly the variable scales and, consequently, the gross national income per capita (GNI) with much larger values and standard deviation compared to other variables explains, practically, all variation in the data.

FOURTH, I interpreted the principal components (PC) of the PCA based on the standardized human data.

The first PC explained 54% of variation in the data. It associated positively with education and life-expectancy and negatively with poor maternal well-being including maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate. These two aspects, high education and poor maternal well-being, can be understood as contradictory indicators for the condition of society.

The second PC explained 16% of variation in the data. It associated positively with female participation in the society including proportions of females in the labor force and parliament. This PC indicates how well females are able to affect the society via working life and politics.

The MCA was performed on 300 individuals and six variables describing their habits of tea drinking. The first four dimensions explained over 50% of variation in the data (see the scree plot). In a biplot, distances between points represent similarity (short distance) or dissimilarity (long distance) between variables. In the biplot based on Dimensions 1 and 2, variables describing the use of sugar and the role of lunch in tea drinking are located rather close to each other, which indicates similarity across these variable categories. Moreover, the how and where variable categories are closely associated with each other so that unpackaged relates to tea shop and tea bag relates to chain store. These two categories, how and where, result in the highest eta2-values in Dimensions 1 and 2.
